<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-48-1091 </DOCNO><TEXT>Patients with primary systemic amyloidosis usually have gastrointestinal(GI) involvement. Although gut involvements is often asymptomatic, depositionof amyloid may cause widespread dysfunction and a variety of radiographicappearances on barium enema examinations. Forty-seven patients with primaryamyloidosis and positive GT biopsies were studied. Of the 47,20 had abnormalbarium enema examinations on one or more occasions; the studies disclosedmotility disturbances, submucosal masses, mucosal fold abnormalities,bowel dilatation, malabsorption patterns, and ulcers. Radiographic abnormalities,while nonspecific, usually correlated with the severity of GI complaints.Additional cases from the Mayo Clinic files are presented to demonstratethe wide spectrum of charges seen in patients with amyloidosis.</TEXT></DOC>